        <h1>How to Tweet With Your Location</h1>
      </div>

      <p>If you are not sure what tweeting with your location is, please visit our <a href="https://support.twitter.com/articles/78525-about-the-tweet-location-feature" title="About Tweet With Your Location">FAQs about Tweet Location</a>&nbsp;help page for more information.&nbsp;</p>
<h3>How to enable tweeting with your location:</h3>
<p>Because tweeting with your location is disabled by default for  everyone, you must enable this feature by following these steps:</p>
<ol>
<li>Click on the <strong>gear icon</strong> in the upper right hand corner of your screen and select <strong>Settings</strong> from the drop down menu.&nbsp;</li>
<li>Go to your&nbsp;<a href="http://twitter.com/settings/account"><strong>Account settings</strong></a>. </li>
<li>At the bottom of the page, check the box next to <strong>Add a location to your Tweets.</strong></li>
<li>You will be prompted to <strong>enter your password</strong>, click <strong>Save</strong> to confirm the change.</li>
</ol>
<p><img src="http://a0.twimg.com/help/1346194050_20166" width="500" /></p>
<h3>How to choose your location:</h3>
<p>After you've enabled Tweet location in your settings, you'll see a location field below the "What's happening?" box on your homepage.</p>
<ol>
<li> Click the <strong>location icon</strong>&nbsp;to see the drop down menu from which you can select your location.</li>
<li>Your selected location will show up with a green check mark.</li>
<li>Click any location listed, or you can <strong>Search for a neighborhood or city</strong>&nbsp;by using the search field the top of the menu.</li>
<li>If you no longer want include location on your Tweets,  simply <strong>click the x next to Turn off location</strong>. This turns location off on a per-Tweet basis.</li>
</ol>
<div class="alert-message block-message info"><strong>Note:</strong> you may be asked by Firefox or Safari "Remember Your Location" or to "Share Location". Click "Yes" if asked.</div>
<p><img src="http://a1.twimg.com/help/1349817945_51046" /></p>
<h3>How to remove location data:</h3>
<p>If you have already enabled tweeting with your location, you can disable it the same way you enabled it:</p>
<ol>
<li>Click on the <strong>gear icon</strong> in the upper right hand corner of your screen and select&nbsp;<strong>Settings</strong>&nbsp;from the drop down menu.&nbsp;</li>
<li>Go to your&nbsp;<a href="http://twitter.com/settings/account"><strong>Account&nbsp;settings</strong></a>.</li>
<li>At the bottom of the page, uncheck the box next to&nbsp;<strong>Add a location to your Tweets</strong>.</li>
<li>You will be prompted to&nbsp;<strong>enter your password</strong>, click&nbsp;<strong>Save</strong>&nbsp;to confirm the change.</li>
</ol>
<p>Making this change only alters your settings going forward.&nbsp;To remove your location data from <strong>all</strong>&nbsp;of your previous Tweets, you&rsquo;ll need to&nbsp;<strong>delete all location information. </strong>Here's how:</p>
<ol>
<li>Delete the Tweet with the location data attached.</li>
<li>Remove all location data from all of your Tweets by clicking on <strong>Delete all location information</strong>&nbsp;in your Account&nbsp;settings. This can take up to 30 minutes, but it will scrub all location   information from prior Tweets. </li>
</ol>
<p><img src="http://a1.twimg.com/help/1346194161_22449" width="500" /></p>
<div class="alert-message block-message info"><strong>IMPORTANT SECURITY NOTE:</strong> It is important to note that deleting location information in your settings does not guarantee the information will be removed from all copies of the data on&nbsp;third-party applications&nbsp;or in external search results.</div>
<div class="alert-message block-message warning">
<p><strong>Related Articles:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/articles/78525">FAQs About Tweet Location</a></li>
<li><a href="/articles/118492-how-to-tweet-with-your-location-on-mobile-devices">How To Tweet With Your Location on Mobile Devices</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Having Trouble?</h3>
<p>Check out our <a href="http://support.twitter.com/groups/32-something-s-not-working#topic_119">Tweet &amp; DM Troubleshooting section</a> for solutions to common problems.</p>

